[[File:Elvisisalive.png|thumb|A cover from the July 23, 1991, issue of ''[[Weekly World News]]'']] '''Elvis sightings''' are reported sightings of singer [[Elvis Presley]] following his death in 1977. The [[conspiracy theory]] that Presley did not die and instead went into hiding was popularized by [[Gail Brewer-Giorgio]] and other authors.
== Notable sighting claims == The earliest known alleged sighting was at the [[Memphis International Airport]] where a man resembling Presley gave the name "Jon Burrows", which was the same name Presley used when booking hotels.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Partridge|first1=Kenneth|title=Suspicious Minds: The Bizarre, 40-Year History of Elvis Presley Sightings|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/503466/suspicious-minds-bizarre-40-year-history-elvis-presley-sightings|accessdate=January 6, 2018|date=August 14, 2017|language=en}}</ref> A series of alleged sightings took place in [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]], in the late 1980s. Such reports encountered much public ridicule and became fodder for humorous publications like the ''[[Weekly World News]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schmidt|first1=William E.|title=Vicksburg Journal; Someplace for the King to Call Home|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/10/17/us/vicksburg-journal-someplace-for-the-king-to-call-home.html|accessdate=January 6, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 17, 1988}}</ref>
Presley was rumored to have appeared in the background of an airport scene in the 1990 film ''[[Home Alone]]''. It was alleged that a bearded man wearing a turtleneck and a sports jacket could be seen over the left shoulder of [[Catherine O'Hara]]'s character while she is arguing with an airline employee. Paranormal researcher [[Ben Radford]] responded to Elvis sighting believers with "Why fake your death and then turn up as an extra in a popular movie? How could the cast and crew have failed to notice the presence of one of the most famous figures in the world? Even if he looked very different could he have disguised his voice and mannerisms?". Radford was challenged to find the actor who played that part to prove it was not Presley. He explained that the burden of proof was on the person making the claim.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Radford |first1=Ben |authorlink=Ben Radford|title=Is Elvis Presley in Home Alone? |journal=Skeptical Inquirer |date=2018 |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=26–27 |publisher=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[USA Today]]'', director [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]] responded "If Elvis was on the set, I would have known".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexander|first1=Bryan|title='Home Alone': Still a scream 25 years later|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/05/home-alone-turns-25-macaulay-culkin/73290704/|accessdate=December 12, 2016|work=USA Today|date=October 5, 2015}}</ref>
After being challenged by Radford to locate the true identity of this extra, Kenny Biddle investigated and found the man to be Gary Richard Grott, who passed away of a heart attack in February 2016. Biddle located Grott's son, Roman, who explained that his father was indeed the extra in the airport scene of ''Home Alone'', and that he had known director Chris Columbus personally. Because of this he appeared in a number of his movies as an extra, including ''Home Alone''.<ref name="Biddle">{{cite web |last1=Biddle |first1=Kenny |title=Busting the ‘Elvis Presley in Home Alone’ Movie Myth |website=csicop.org |publisher=CFI |url=https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/busting_the_lsquoelvis_presley_in_home_alonersquo_movie_myth|accessdate=October 25, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025035243/https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/busting_the_lsquoelvis_presley_in_home_alonersquo_movie_myth |archivedate=October 25, 2018}}</ref>
[[Bill Bixby]], who co-starred with Presley in ''[[Clambake (film)|Clambake]]'' and ''[[Speedway (1968 film)|Speedway]]'', hosted two [[television special]]s investigating the conspiracy: ''The Elvis Files'' (1991)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kogan|first1=Rick|title=The Once And Future King|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-08-13/features/9103280328_1_graceland-bathroom-elvis-files-future-king|accessdate=January 6, 2018|work=Chicago Tribune|date=August 13, 1991|language=en}}</ref> and ''The Elvis Conspiracy'' (1992).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kogan|first1=Rick|title=`Anything But Love` Axed By Studio And Abc|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-22/features/9201070160_1_show-syndication-studio-and-abc|accessdate=January 6, 2018|work=Evening: Best on TV|date=January 22, 1992|language=en}}</ref> The conspiracy was also featured in the 1990 video game, ''[[Les Manley in: Search for the King]]'', where the titular hero attempts to find Presley (known in the game as "the King") to win a million-dollar contest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cobbett|first1=Richard|title=Crap Shoot: Les Manley: Search For THE KING|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/crap-shoot-les-manley-search-for-the-king/|accessdate=January 14, 2018|work=PC Gamer|date=December 24, 2010|language=en}}</ref>
