'''Imene reo metua''': a [[Cook Islands]] / Rarotongan term; (literally 'hymn/s of the parent/ancestor'): they are formal traditional songs with tune and harmony, which are distinguished from the [[imene tuki]] style of the Cook Islands which are less formal, often grunted verses with nonsense syllables included for rhythmic effect.<ref>{{cite book|title=Weavers of Song: Polynesian Music and Dance|first=Mervyn|last=McLean|page=482|publisher=Auckland University Press|year=1999|location=Aukland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GhEpKUITQUIC&pg=PA482#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
