The '''Royal Hanneford Circus''' is an [[United States|American]]-based touring family [[circus]]. With origins dating back to 1690, it has been called the oldest circus in the world.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19890714&id=iZYWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pxIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3218,3090241 |title=Oldest circus shines at a new site |first=Jay |last=Joslyn |publisher=''Milwaukee Sentinel'' |date=14 July 1989 |accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref> The family first performed as a traveling troupe in 1807. In 1903, the family began its own circus as the "Hanneford Royal Canadian Circus" and in their early seasons toured the [[British Isles]] and [[Continental Europe]].<ref name=sahib>{{cite web |url=http://sahibshrine.org/circus/hanneford.htm |title=History of the Royal Hanneford Circus |publisher=Sahib Shriners |accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> The family performed separately throughout much of the early 20th century in the United States. The modern Royal Hanneford Circus was formed in 1965, when Tommy Hanneford began producing shows featuring the family.
==History== ===Early origins=== Accounts of the early origins of the Hanneford family performances conflict. Some accounts claim that the Hanneford family began performing as early as 1690, when the [[Ireland|Irish]]-born Michael Hanneford entertained royalty with [[bareback riding]], [[acrobatics]], and [[juggling]].<ref name=spt>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19961011&id=fdAMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BF8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3808,1213402 |title=Royal Hanneford Circus rides into Tampa |first=Logan |last=Neill |publisher=''St. Petersburg Times'' |date=11 October 1996 |accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=tb>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19951022&id=DRQVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3950,7236924 |title=Rare white tigers and magic hoops |first=Natasha |last=Rafi |publisher=''Toledo Blade'' |date=22 October 1995 |accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> The family themselves claim their oldest involvement with the circus involved Edwin Hanneford, a juggler from [[London]]. In 1778, Edwin was summoned by [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]] to compete against Walter Scott to determine the best juggler in [[England]]. However, during the competition, King George became too preoccupied with [[American Revolutionary War|other issues]] and did not declare a winner.<ref name=history>{{cite web |url=http://www.hannefordcircus.com/page4.html |title=Historical Overview of the Royal Hanneford Circus |publisher=Royal Hanneford Circus |accessdate=17 December 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604100028/http://www.hannefordcircus.com/page4.html |archivedate=4 June 2009 |df= }}</ref>
===European traveling shows=== The Hanneford family first traveled as a [[:wikt:troupe|troupe]] in 1807. Successive generations of the family were involved in performances as well. By 1903, the family had their own circus production, the Hanneford Royal Canadian Circus. They performed under a [[canvas]] tent and traveled to cities and villages in the [[British Isles]] via horse-drawn wagons. During the winter months they performed with other acts indoors throughout [[Europe]].<ref name=sahib/> In 1915 the family was performing in [[Spain]] while [[John Ringling]] of the [[Ringling Brothers Circus]] was in attendance. After seeing the production, Ringling wanted to bring the family to perform in the [[United States]]. In order to do so, Ringling purchased the entire circus. At that time, the family consisted of George Hanneford Sr. and his wife Catherine, Edwin "Poodles", George, Grace, and Elizabeth.<ref name=cmu>{{cite web |url=http://clarke.cmich.edu/current_exhibit/major_circus_families.html |title=Michigan Circus Families |publisher=Clarke Historical Library |accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>
====Edwin "Poodles" Hanneford==== {{Infobox person | name = "Poodles" Hanneford | image = | caption = <small>''Poodles'' Hanneford and family</small> |image_size = 240px | birth_name = Edwin Hanneford | birth_date = {{Birth date|1891|06|14|df=y}} | birth_place = Barnsby, [[Yorkshire]], [[England]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1967|12|09|1891|06|14|df=y}} | death_place = [[Kattskill Bay, New York]], U.S. | occupation = Comedian, Acrobat | years_active = | religion = | spouse = Grace Norma | children = }} '''Edwin "Poodles" Hanneford''' is considered amongst the greatest [[Horse riding stunts|trick riders]] in history. He was the first to perform a [[somersault]] from one running horse to another. Additionally, Poodles held a [[Guinness Book of World Records]] record for performing a running jump onto a horse and stepping off 26 times in a row. Poodles appeared in over 40 films. He retired in 1954, died in 1967, and was enshrined in the [[International Circus Hall of Fame]] in 1968.<ref name=cmu/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0360372/ |title=Poodles Hanneford |publisher=Internet Movie Database |accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref> {{clear}}
===United States=== Upon coming to the United States, the Hannefords performed with various acts. The family's first credited appearance in American film is ''[[When I Grow Up (film)|When I Grow Up]]'', released in 1951.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}
The next [[patriarch]] after Poodles was Tommy Hanneford, son of George Sr. and nephew of Poodles, who began performing as a clown in 1933 when he was five years old. He was called "The Funniest Man on Horseback" for his comic equestrian performances. He performed from the 1930s through the 1960s, except for a period beginning in 1946 when he served in the [[United States Army]]. Besides his circus performances he appeared on television, in films, and at most major [[Shrine Circus|Shrine circuses]] throughout the United States.<ref name=cmu/> The family was considered reunited in 1965 at [[Pleasure Island (Massachusetts amusement park)|Pleasure Island Park]] in [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]]. Tommy organized the performance that featured his sister Kay with a dog act, his wife Struppi on a [[tightrope walking|high wire]], and was called the Hanneford Family Circus. Tommy later [[incorporation (business)|incorporated]] the act in [[Macon, Georgia]] and it became the first time the family had owned their own circus since his father George Sr.<ref name=sahib/>
The family's first major production was in September 1966 in [[Saginaw, Michigan]]. Tommy's brother George Jr. was featured in a bareback riding act. The performance is considered the first of the "Royal Hanneford Circus". In 1968, Tommy joined producer Bill English, and in 1969 the two men were joined by Art Concello, formerly general manager of the [[Ringling Bros. and Barnum & Bailey Circus]]. The three men operated Circus Classics, Inc. until they separated in 1974. In 1975, Tommy reorganized the Royal Hanneford Circus.<ref name=sahib/>
George Sr. Hanneford was inducted into the Circus Hall of Fame in 1977, his wife Catherine in 1990, and Tommy posthumously in 2008, following his death in 2005.<ref name=cmu/> Tommy's wife Struppi was inducted into the Circus Hall of Fame in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Circus Hall of Fame Inductees|url=http://visit.circushalloffame.com/circus-hall-of-fame-inductees/|website=Circus Hall of Fame|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>
====Fort Lauderdale Swap Shop==== In 1989, the Royal Hanneford Circus began performing at the [[Fort Lauderdale Swap Shop]], performing every day of the week save for Tuesdays. Following the death of Tommy, his brother George Jr. and sister Catherine assumed control of the circus. In 1993, the Swap Shop owner Preston Henn had been sued over injury to a circus performer, leading him to require the circus to provide worker's compensation insurance to its employees. In July 2006, the circus was evicted from the Swap Shop for violating that agreement.<ref name=sstl>{{cite web |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/sfl-ccircus12aug12-story.html |title=Friday hearing delayed after Swap Shop owner closes curtain on circus |publisher=Sun Sentinel |accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref>
Prior to the eviction, the circus employed about a dozen performers and owned nine animals. The use of animals in the Hannefords' circus acts at the Swap Shop attracted the attention of animal rights activists, including the Animal Rights Foundation of Florida (ARFF), which had long accused the circus of animal cruelty. However, George Jr.'s son, George Hanneford III, denied these claims, as well as rebuffed an offer from ARFF to adopt and relocate the animals.<ref name=sstl></ref>
